whole, like, self-doubt thing.

00:34:24.610 --> 00:34:26.520
They had no confidence
in themselves.

00:34:26.520 --> 00:34:28.610
So I was just
curious, like your--

00:34:28.610 --> 00:34:30.979
I don't know-- ideas on
targeting a younger audience.

00:34:30.979 --> 00:34:33.520
ANDREW HORN: Yeah, you know, so
Tribute's target demographics

00:34:33.520 --> 00:34:36.290
and where we focus on
is on the 18 and above.

00:34:36.290 --> 00:34:38.679
So where people kind of
have a little more emotional

00:34:38.679 --> 00:34:41.270
intelligence and are capable
of articulating these things.

00:34:41.270 --> 00:34:43.710
So it's not where I've spent
most of my time at Tribute,

00:34:43.710 --> 00:34:46.210
but it was where I spent a great
deal of my time with Dreams

00:34:46.210 --> 00:34:48.159
For Kids.

00:34:48.159 --> 00:34:49.659
And I think that
what we always lead

00:34:49.659 --> 00:34:52.600
with when it comes to kids,
again, are some of these values

00:34:52.600 --> 00:34:55.300
that we talked about of leading
with kindness before we get

00:34:55.300 --> 00:34:56.980
to the communication aspect.

00:34:56.980 --> 00:34:59.530
It's establishing that as
the foundation of interaction

00:34:59.530 --> 00:35:02.180
between people of just
being able to ask yourself,

00:35:02.180 --> 00:35:03.770
is this a kind thing?

00:35:03.770 --> 00:35:06.850
And so I mean, when we
were at Dreams For Kids, we

00:35:06.850 --> 00:35:10.390
had this thing that we embraced
at any one of our events,

00:35:10.390 --> 00:35:13.420
because we were dealing with a
lot of kids with disabilities,

00:35:13.420 --> 00:35:18.760
is if you're ever unsure,
the general consensus

00:35:18.760 --> 00:35:20.770
was that you just
go over and you ask.

00:35:20.770 --> 00:35:22.840
And everyone just
seeks to understand.

00:35:22.840 --> 00:35:24.910
And it was basically
setting this baseline

00:35:24.910 --> 00:35:28.266
of understanding between people
rather than making judgments,

00:35:28.266 --> 00:35:29.390
and all these other things.

00:35:29.390 --> 00:35:31.960
So I think, again, you know,
I don't do a lot of work

00:35:31.960 --> 00:35:32.930
directly with kids.

00:35:32.930 --> 00:35:35.350
But I think that establishing
that understanding

00:35:35.350 --> 00:35:37.930
of seeking to understand
your counterpart

00:35:37.930 --> 00:35:41.290
and asking questions will still
be a virtuous path, right?

00:35:41.290 --> 00:35:43.571
I mean, when you think about
your time as a counselor,

00:35:43.571 --> 00:35:45.820
what were the biggest
challenges that young girls were

00:35:45.820 --> 00:35:47.170
finding with being vulnerable?

00:35:47.170 --> 00:35:48.370
Just that they were
being attacked,

00:35:48.370 --> 00:35:50.020
or they weren't receiving
that back to them, or--

00:35:50.020 --> 00:35:50.290
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:35:50.290 --> 00:35:51.415
A little bit of everything.

00:35:51.415 --> 00:35:53.470
I think part of it was
too, like, they couldn't

00:35:53.470 --> 00:35:56.830
find an authentic voice,
because everything

00:35:56.830 --> 00:36:01.500
was done for a like on
Instagram or for a retweet,

00:36:01.500 --> 00:36:02.759
or whatever it was.

00:36:02.759 --> 00:36:05.050
And they would give each
other compliments on Instagram

00:36:05.050 --> 00:36:07.720
just to get it back so
that they could look at it

00:36:07.720 --> 00:36:10.729
and say, I have 500 comments
of how great I look, you know?

00:36:10.729 --> 00:36:12.520
ANDREW HORN: So I'm so
happy you said that,

00:36:12.520 --> 00:36:14.645
because it really did just
trigger something in me.

00:36:14.645 --> 00:36:17.724
And you know, my reality is
that I wasn't a great student

00:36:17.724 --> 00:36:19.390
throughout high school
and even college.

00:36:19.390 --> 00:36:21.640
It's kind of like, I went
through and I got grades,

00:36:21.640 --> 00:36:25.360
but I was never fully
present there or valued it.

00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:28.150
And no kind of
guidance, no speakers,

00:36:28.150 --> 00:36:30.400
no counselors ever
connected with me

00:36:30.400 --> 00:36:33.940
and gave me insight or advice
about how to evaluate the world

00:36:33.940 --> 00:36:36.650
or how I wanted to live my
life that really connected.

00:36:36.650 --> 00:36:38.140
And so when we
talk about starting

00:36:38.140 --> 00:36:40.720
with the art of meaningful
conversation and questions,

00:36:40.720 --> 00:36:43.300
I think that, again, is
the best place to start.

00:36:43.300 --> 00:36:45.430
Because if you
empower young people

00:36:45.430 --> 00:36:48.640
at a young age with a
foundational sense of self--

00:36:48.640 --> 00:36:50.395
who they are, what's
important to them--

00:36:50.395 --> 00:36:52.270
I think that that's the
most important thing.

00:36:52.270 --> 00:36:55.270
And again, you can give
that to a younger person

00:36:55.270 --> 00:36:57.310
and say, here are
some of the questions

00:36:57.310 --> 00:36:58.992
that you can explore
for yourself.

00:36:58.992 --> 00:37:00.700
And when you can relay
that directly back

00:37:00.700 --> 00:37:03.520
to social anxiety and shyness
and some of those things

00:37:03.520 --> 00:37:06.490
that are much more prevalent
in high school and college,

00:37:06.490 --> 00:37:08.740
then what happens is that
you give people a foundation

00:37:08.740 --> 00:37:12.550
to say, before you can feel
confident in these situations,

00:37:12.550 --> 00:37:15.310
like, the most important
thing is truly understanding,

00:37:15.310 --> 00:37:17.274
trusting, and loving yourself.

00:37:17.274 --> 00:37:18.940
And so we can give
that to young people.

00:37:18.940 --> 00:37:20.770
I think that that's always
where I would start,

00:37:20.770 --> 00:37:22.186
is not telling one
to do anything,

00:37:22.186 --> 00:37:24.790
but providing them with the
construct to actually perform

00:37:24.790 --> 00:37:27.070
that kind of
introspection that leads

00:37:27.070 --> 00:37:28.840
to virtuous
interactions, connection,

00:37:28.840 --> 00:37:31.020
connecting with the type
of people that we need to.

00:37:31.020 --> 00:37:31.250
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:37:31.250 --> 00:37:32.350
It's like almost
trying to get it

00:37:32.350 --> 00:37:34.840
proactive rather than reactive,
because that was like--

00:37:34.840 --> 00:37:37.550
we were trying to put out
fires almost, you know?

00:37:37.550 --> 00:37:39.209
And it was hard to
do at that point.

00:37:39.209 --> 00:37:40.750
ANDREW HORN: Yeah,
my mom always says

00:37:40.750 --> 00:37:46.390
that the wisest teachers are
the greatest question askers.

00:37:46.390 --> 00:37:48.010
And so that's what
I would emphasize.

00:37:48.010 --> 00:37:48.550
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:37:48.550 --> 00:37:49.000
Thank you.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:50.250
ANDREW HORN: Yeah, absolutely.

