00:41:04.400 --> 00:41:06.520
younger people,
children, you know,

00:41:06.520 --> 00:41:08.674
as a relatively new father--

00:41:08.674 --> 00:41:09.590
ANDREW HORN: Congrats.

00:41:09.590 --> 00:41:12.220
AUDIENCE: --and, you know,
speaking from my own experience

00:41:12.220 --> 00:41:15.850
on Facebook, it's
been my feeling

00:41:15.850 --> 00:41:19.750
pretty early on that
a lot of people I know

00:41:19.750 --> 00:41:24.220
have exchanged a few
meaningful relationships

00:41:24.220 --> 00:41:27.580
with a lot of meaningless
ones, and a lot of really

00:41:27.580 --> 00:41:28.300
shallow ones.

00:41:28.300 --> 00:41:30.790
They've really kind of
replaced depth with breadth,

00:41:30.790 --> 00:41:33.700
and we're not talking
to each other anymore.

00:41:33.700 --> 00:41:35.110
We're broadcasting.

00:41:35.110 --> 00:41:35.610
Right?

00:41:35.610 --> 00:41:38.350
And we're advertising,
so to speak.

00:41:38.350 --> 00:41:40.154
At least some of us do.

00:41:40.154 --> 00:41:42.070
And it's certainly the
experience on Facebook,

00:41:42.070 --> 00:41:45.450
you know, browsing
Facebook, it's

00:41:45.450 --> 00:41:49.430
an inescapable
experience of comparison.

00:41:49.430 --> 00:41:51.370
And since you
quoted Brene Brown,

00:41:51.370 --> 00:41:52.630
I'm sure you know her works.

00:41:52.630 --> 00:41:57.520
And you know, comparison is
the pathway to feeling less,

00:41:57.520 --> 00:41:58.500
to feeling ashamed.

00:42:01.660 --> 00:42:05.630
And I feel that I myself, you
know, I'm fairly immune to it.

00:42:05.630 --> 00:42:06.430
Not completely.

00:42:06.430 --> 00:42:10.390
At least, I'm smart enough
to avoid exposing myself

00:42:10.390 --> 00:42:11.500
to too much of that.

00:42:14.260 --> 00:42:18.550
Are there tangible
things that we

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:23.260
can do to help children
develop that immunity

00:42:23.260 --> 00:42:26.470
to the inescapable
world around us

00:42:26.470 --> 00:42:29.530
where there'll be a lot of
people that are shallow,

00:42:29.530 --> 00:42:31.450
there'll be a lot
of people that will

00:42:31.450 --> 00:42:35.710
judge them using meaningless
tools like likes, et cetera?

00:42:35.710 --> 00:42:40.030
And you know, obviously,
developing self-worth,

00:42:40.030 --> 00:42:42.760
developing integrity,
these are principles

00:42:42.760 --> 00:42:43.840
I can easily agree with.

00:42:43.840 --> 00:42:48.200
But are there good tricks to
do that I guess is my question.

00:42:48.200 --> 00:42:49.200
ANDREW HORN: Absolutely.

00:42:49.200 --> 00:42:52.107
Well, I'll expand on
the comparison theme,

00:42:52.107 --> 00:42:54.190
and then get right back
into how we can apply this

00:42:54.190 --> 00:42:56.890
to young people and their
browsing and social media

00:42:56.890 --> 00:42:58.300
habits.

00:42:58.300 --> 00:43:01.780
One of my favorite
concepts with comparison

00:43:01.780 --> 00:43:05.680
is the idea that comparison
is the thief of joy.

00:43:05.680 --> 00:43:08.050
And I just notice this
in any given moment where

00:43:08.050 --> 00:43:12.190
I find myself comparing
to a competitor,

00:43:12.190 --> 00:43:14.530
to someone else who's
finding success.

00:43:14.530 --> 00:43:17.050
And in those moments
where you feel

00:43:17.050 --> 00:43:22.464
jealousy or angst, whatever it
might be when you're comparing,

00:43:22.464 --> 00:43:24.880
my first thought there, and
what I've trained myself to do

00:43:24.880 --> 00:43:28.870
is to realize that that
comparison and that malice,

00:43:28.870 --> 00:43:31.580
or whatever it might
be, is nothing--

00:43:31.580 --> 00:43:33.340
it has nothing to
do with that person.

00:43:33.340 --> 00:43:36.280
It's purely internal, and it
says something about myself.

00:43:36.280 --> 00:43:38.170
And so I think about
the transformation

00:43:38.170 --> 00:43:42.940
of comparing to celebrating,
which is what we want to do.

00:43:42.940 --> 00:43:47.380
Is that if we cannot celebrate
the successes of other people,

00:43:47.380 --> 00:43:52.720
it only says something about
us and our own insecurities.

00:43:52.720 --> 00:43:55.590
So it's that shift from
comparing to celebrating.

00:43:55.590 --> 00:43:58.060
And if we cannot celebrate,
we can acknowledge that

00:43:58.060 --> 00:43:59.710
it's because of our
own insecurities,

00:43:59.710 --> 00:44:03.310
and something to be worked
on, because no one is perfect.

00:44:03.310 --> 00:44:05.560
And as it relates
to young people,

00:44:05.560 --> 00:44:07.630
I think, again,
rather than telling

00:44:07.630 --> 00:44:10.990
them what to do, the
best thing that we

00:44:10.990 --> 00:44:13.330
can do with young
people is to ask them

00:44:13.330 --> 00:44:15.220
why they are doing
things, and to help them

00:44:15.220 --> 00:44:17.500
come to their own realizations.

00:44:17.500 --> 00:44:19.582
And again, how we do that
is with good questions.

00:44:19.582 --> 00:44:21.040
And I'll revert
back to one that we

00:44:21.040 --> 00:44:22.930
talked about earlier,
which is, if you

00:44:22.930 --> 00:44:25.270
have a young person who's
posting on Instagram

00:44:25.270 --> 00:44:28.420
or is typing these types of
comments, to simply ask them,

00:44:28.420 --> 00:44:30.479
like, why are you doing that?

00:44:30.479 --> 00:44:32.770
And to see what kind of answer
that they actually have,

00:44:32.770 --> 00:44:34.930
to actually help them
identify those motivations

00:44:34.930 --> 00:44:38.200
for themselves, to see if
it's something that they like.

00:44:38.200 --> 00:44:40.780
And again, we all remember
our younger years,

00:44:40.780 --> 00:44:43.190
and it's like, we are
hardwired to rebel.

00:44:43.190 --> 00:44:45.040
And so when someone
is telling us

00:44:45.040 --> 00:44:46.961
that this is the
way to do something,

00:44:46.961 --> 00:44:49.210
we're going to be very
resistant for anyone to tell us

00:44:49.210 --> 00:44:52.310
what to do when we're still
formulating our own identity.

00:44:52.310 --> 00:44:54.340
But when we can give
people a construct

00:44:54.340 --> 00:44:56.560
to do that meaningful
introspection for themself,

00:44:56.560 --> 00:44:58.780
I think that is probably
the most effective path

00:44:58.780 --> 00:45:00.670
to help them evaluate
those things.

00:45:00.670 --> 00:45:02.290
So again, it's
just understanding

00:45:02.290 --> 00:45:04.810
why they're doing these
things, and hopefully

00:45:04.810 --> 00:45:07.300
encouraging designers
and people at Google

00:45:07.300 --> 00:45:09.670
to be thoughtful about how
we are designing products

00:45:09.670 --> 00:45:11.890
and what we're
defining as success.

